# Browser Testing — Mistakes to Avoid

## 1. Clear Vite cache after installing packages

After `npm install` of new packages, the dev server will crash with 500 / 504 errors.
Always do this before restarting:

```bash
rm -rf node_modules/.vite
```

## 2. Flush server cache after changing decode/render logic

Content fetched from GitHub is cached in memory (or Redis). If you fix how content is decoded or rendered, the old broken result is still cached. Flush it:

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:5173/api/webhook -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"ref":"refs/heads/github"}'
```

Don't waste tool calls debugging "why didn't my fix work" — it's the cache.

## 3. httpOnly cookies can't be set via JavaScript

The `gh_token` cookie is `httpOnly: true`. You cannot set it with `document.cookie` or `javascript:` URLs. Use the server-side dev endpoint instead:

```
GET /api/auth/dev-token?token=<GITHUB_PAT>
```

Then navigate to any URL with `#token=<PAT>` and hard-reload to also populate localStorage (needed for Edit/Drafts buttons in the Header).

The test PAT is stored in `.env` as `GITHUB_TEST_PAT`. Read it from there — never hardcode it.

## 4. The Edit button only appears on content pages

Don't navigate to `/` and expect to see the Edit button. The home page has no `sourcePath`. Navigate to a wiki content page like `/chapters/...` to test editing.

## 5. Element missing from accessibility snapshot — diagnostic flowchart

When you add `role`, `aria-label`, or `data-testid` to an element and it still doesn't appear in `browser_snapshot`, follow these steps **in order**. Do NOT guess — each step is one `javascript:void(...)` call.

**Step 1 — Does the element exist in the DOM?**

```
javascript:void(document.title = document.querySelectorAll('.my-selector').length + ' found')
```

- **0 found** → The library isn't rendering your content. Check the library's API docs for `template`, `content`, or `render` options.
- **N found** → Go to step 2.

**Step 2 — Are your custom attributes present?**

```
javascript:void(document.title = document.querySelector('.my-selector')?.getAttribute('role') + '|' + document.querySelector('.my-selector')?.getAttribute('aria-label'))
```

- **null|null** → The library has a **sanitizer stripping attributes**. Search docs/issues for "xss", "sanitize", "whitelist", or "filterOptions". In this project: vis-timeline strips all non-whitelisted attributes; fix with `xss: { disabled: true }` in dev mode.
- **Values present** → Go to step 3.

**Step 3 — Is the element visually hidden?**

```
javascript:void(document.title = getComputedStyle(document.querySelector('.my-selector')).visibility + '|' + getComputedStyle(document.querySelector('.my-selector')).display)
```

- **hidden|*anything*** → `visibility: hidden` removes elements from the accessibility tree. Override with CSS `visibility: visible !important`. In this project: SvelteFlow uses `visibility: hidden` for node measurement.
- **visible|none** → `display: none` fully hides the element. Check if a parent conditionally hides it.
- **visible|*not none*** → Go to step 4.

**Step 4 — Is an ancestor hiding the subtree?**

```
javascript:void(document.title = document.querySelector('.my-selector')?.closest('[aria-hidden="true"]')?.className || 'no aria-hidden ancestor')
```

- **Found ancestor** → A parent has `aria-hidden="true"`, which removes the entire subtree from the accessibility tree. Override it or move your element outside.
- **No ancestor** → The issue is something else (z-index clipping, iframe boundary, or a browser_snapshot tool limitation). Take a screenshot to verify the element is visually present.

**This flowchart costs 1-4 tool calls. Without it, diagnosis takes 8-15.**
